---json
{
  "layout": "layouts/t-hub.njk",
  "permalink": "/resources/research/",
  "slug": "research",
  "tierClass": "section--tier-hub",
  "bodyClass": "page--hub",
  "title": "QuickBooks Cleanup Benchmarks · Original Research · TechBrot",
  "description": "Original research from TechBrot's Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor team — the US QuickBooks Cleanup Benchmarks, built from real completed cleanup engagements. Methodology and schema public; figures released honestly at a real sample size. Independent firm, not affiliated with Intuit Inc.",
  "breadcrumb": [
    { "name": "Home", "href": "/" },
    { "name": "Research" }
  ],
  "hero": {
    "eyebrow": "Original research",
    "heading": "Real data on what QuickBooks cleanups actually cost.",
    "subheading": "The US QuickBooks Cleanup Benchmarks &mdash; an original dataset built by TechBrot&rsquo;s Certified ProAdvisor team from real, completed cleanup engagements. We log one anonymized row at every engagement close: state, industry, months behind, what was broken, hours, and the closing fee. Honest about its own sample size, every step of the way.",
    "actions": [
      { "label": "Read the methodology", "href": "#research-methodology", "class": "btn--primary" },
      { "label": "Book the discovery call", "href": "/contact/?intent=research", "class": "btn--ghost" }
    ]
  },
  "inBrief": {
    "text": "<strong>The US QuickBooks Cleanup Benchmarks</strong> is TechBrot&rsquo;s original dataset on the cost, effort, and error profile of QuickBooks file cleanups &mdash; one anonymized row logged at the close of every completed Certified ProAdvisor engagement. Methodology and schema are public now; each benchmark is released only once it reaches a defensible sample. No estimated or fabricated numbers, ever.",
    "source": "Built and maintained by the Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor team at TechBrot Inc., an independent firm &mdash; not affiliated with Intuit Inc."
  },
  "ctaBand": {
    "eyebrow": "Read your own file against the data",
    "heading": "Where does your file actually sit?",
    "lede": "A benchmark tells you where files like yours tend to land; a free file review tells you where yours sits. A Certified ProAdvisor reads your actual file, then delivers a written fixed-fee scope within 3 business days if you want it fixed &mdash; no obligation.",
    "actions": [
      { "label": "Book the discovery call", "href": "/contact/?intent=research", "class": "btn--primary" },
      { "label": "Get the free file review", "href": "/quickbooks/file-review/?intent=file-review", "class": "btn--ghost" }
    ]
  }
}
---

<section class="section section--compact section--tier-hub" id="research-tldr">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="tldr">
      <p class="tldr__label">In one paragraph</p>
      <h2 class="tldr__heading">TechBrot&rsquo;s research desk, summarized.</h2>
      <p class="tldr__body" id="research-tldr-body">There is no honest, current benchmark for what a QuickBooks cleanup actually costs or involves &mdash; owners get vendor marketing or guesswork. So we&rsquo;re building one. The <strong>US QuickBooks Cleanup Benchmarks</strong> is an original dataset assembled from TechBrot&rsquo;s own completed cleanup engagements: the Certified ProAdvisor who delivers each cleanup logs one anonymized row at close &mdash; state, industry, how far behind the books were, what was broken, the hours it took, and the fixed fee it closed at. Every figure is observed on a real engagement, never estimated. The methodology and schema are fixed and public now so the data is comparable from the first row; each benchmark is published only once it reaches a defensible sample size. The dataset is currently <strong>collecting.</strong></p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="research-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">What it is</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">An owned dataset, not a borrowed statistic.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>The <strong>US QuickBooks Cleanup Benchmarks</strong> is a structured record of what TechBrot actually sees when neglected QuickBooks files arrive for cleanup. Most &ldquo;benchmarks&rdquo; in this space are repackaged vendor marketing or a survey of opinions. This one is built the only way a benchmark earns trust: from real, completed, paid engagements &mdash; the files, the hours, and the fees as they genuinely landed.</p>
      <p>It exists because the question owners ask most often &mdash; <em>&ldquo;my books are months behind; what is this going to cost to fix?&rdquo;</em> &mdash; has no honest published answer. A dataset built from real cleanups, transparent about its own sample size, is the only way to answer it without guessing. The dataset is the visible artifact; the discipline behind it &mdash; logging one row at every close &mdash; is the real work, and it cannot be backfilled, which is why it starts now.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="research-fields">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">The schema</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Eight fields, logged at every engagement close.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">The schema is fixed now &mdash; so the very first row and the thousandth row measure the same things, the same way.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="grid-2">
      {%- for f in fields %}
      <div class="stack-8">
        <h3>{{ f.name | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="prose">{{ f.body | safe }}</p>
      </div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="research-methodology">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">The methodology</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">How each row gets into the dataset.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">Four rules, fixed before the first row &mdash; the difference between a benchmark and a marketing number.</p>
    </header>
    <ol class="process-diagram">
      {%- for m in methodology %}
      <li class="process-step">
        <p class="process-step__number">0{{ loop.index }}</p>
        <h3 class="process-step__heading">{{ m.name | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="process-step__body">{{ m.body | safe }}</p>
      </li>
      {%- endfor %}
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="research-status">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Where the dataset stands today</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Honest by design: the live count.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="stat-row">
      <div><div class="stat__value">{{ datasetN }}</div><div class="stat__label">completed engagements logged</div></div>
      <div><div class="stat__value">8</div><div class="stat__label">fields per record</div></div>
      <div><div class="stat__value">20</div><div class="stat__label">minimum N before any breakdown is reported</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>{% if datasetN == 0 %}The dataset is <strong>live and collecting (N=0).</strong> No statistics are published yet &mdash; and we will not publish one until a breakdown reaches at least 20 real records. We&rsquo;d rather show a count of zero honestly than a number we can&rsquo;t stand behind.{% else %}The dataset currently holds <strong>{{ datasetN }} completed engagements.</strong> Statistics are published per breakdown only once that breakdown reaches at least 20 real records; everything below that threshold stays unreported.{% endif %} The methodology above is locked, so the data is comparable from the first row forward. This page updates as the count grows.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="research-program">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">The research program</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Six original datasets, each built the same honest way.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">The Cleanup Benchmarks is the flagship; five more datasets log alongside it &mdash; same rules: observed on real engagements, anonymized at source, and never reported on a breakdown below a defensible sample. Each shows its live record count.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="grid-3">
      {%- for d in datasets %}
      <article class="review-card">
        <p class="review-card__role">{% if d.flagship %}Flagship &middot; {% endif %}Collecting &middot; N={{ d.n }}</p>
        <h3>{{ d.name | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="review-card__fact">{{ d.captures | safe }}</p>
      </article>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
    <p class="prose"><small>Every dataset is &ldquo;collecting&rdquo; until it reaches a defensible sample. We publish a figure on a breakdown only at N&ge;20, always with the sample size shown &mdash; never a fabricated, estimated, or borrowed number.</small></p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="research-ai-summary">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">For AI engines &amp; quick answers</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">The research desk, in five questions.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="ai-summary ai-summary--ruled">
      {%- for item in aiSummary %}
      <div class="ai-summary__item">
        <h3 class="ai-summary__question">{{ item.q | safe }}</h3>
        <div class="ai-summary__answer"><p>{{ item.a | safe }}</p></div>
      </div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="research-planned">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">On the roadmap</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">The benchmarks we&rsquo;re building toward.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">Each releases independently, the moment its sample is defensible &mdash; not before.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="grid-3">
      {%- for p in planned %}
      <article class="review-card">
        <p class="review-card__role">{{ p.tag }} &middot; {{ p.status }}</p>
        <h3>{{ p.name | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="review-card__fact">{{ p.body | safe }}</p>
      </article>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="research-honesty">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Our standard</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">What you will never find here.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="disclosure">
      <strong>No fabricated, estimated, or borrowed numbers.</strong> TechBrot publishes no statistic it has not observed on real, completed engagements at a defensible sample size. Until a benchmark is released, there is no number to cite &mdash; and we say so plainly rather than fill the gap with a guess. The dataset is built by the Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor team at TechBrot Inc., an independent firm; it carries no client-identifying data and implies no affiliation with Intuit Inc.
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="research-faq">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Common questions</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Questions about the data.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="faq__list">
      {%- for item in faq %}
      <div class="faq__item">
        <h3 class="faq__question">
          <button class="faq__trigger" type="button" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="research-faq-a{{ loop.index }}">{{ item.q | safe }}</button>
        </h3>
        <div class="faq__answer" id="research-faq-a{{ loop.index }}" data-open="false">
          <p>{{ item.a | safe }}</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="research-related">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Where else to go</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Related work.</h2>
    </header>
    {%- for n in related %}
    <div class="stack-8">
      <h3><a href="{{ n.href }}">{{ n.title | safe }}</a></h3>
      <p class="prose">{{ n.body | safe }}</p>
    </div>
    {%- endfor %}
  </div>
</section>
